We are running chutes-miner on a 16-node cluster with limited bandwidth (1G total).

----
In the chute you can define`max_instances`, you are charged the standard hourly rate * number of instances while the instances are running, you define a `shutdown_after_seconds` value which says how long to wait after the last request to spin it down, you are charged from the time the instance is hot through last request finish timestamp + shutdown_after_seconds.

Example:
- node selector is 2x h200, deployment cost is 2.7 * 3 * 2 = $16.2
- you specify max_instances = 1, and shutdown_after_seconds = 300
- you send a request at 00:00:00, no instances available yet, bounty created, you wait
  - miner creates the instance at 00:01:00, not hot yet
  - miner finishes spinning up the model at 00:06:00, now hot
- you send as many requests as you want, then stop at 00:11:00
- miner instances are deleted at 00:16:00 (because 5 minute shutdown after time)

Total cost is $16.2 (deployment, one time, won't be charged again for next startup sequence), plus 10 minutes of compute (00:06:00 through 00:11:00 for used compute + 5 minute termination grace period) = 2.7 * 2 * 10 / 60 = $0.9, so $17.1 total

Next iteration, same thing, only 5 minutes of compute (plus 5 grace) = $0.9
